{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"168"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/168"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.1,0.06,0.28,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107104"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89568"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2576"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5572"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44975"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107104"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health assessment. She has recently moved from India to Australia one month ago and lives with her husband. She feels well and has no medical conditions. She is unsure of her childhood vaccinations and has never smoked. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a small scar on her left upper arm consistent with prior BCG vaccination. The remainder of the examination shows no abnormalities. A purified protein derivative tuberculin skin test is performed. Three days later, an induration of 13 mm is noted. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Rifampicin, isoniazid, pyrazinamide, ethambutol","Isoniazid monotherapy","Interferon gamma release assay","Sputum cultures"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a positive tuberculin skin test, which indicates exposure to \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E. In people from high TB-prevalence countries like India, an induration of \u226510mm is considered positive. The next step is to determine whether the infection is active or latent through systematic screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is the essential initial investigation to screen for active tuberculosis. Combined with the clinical history and physical examination (which are normal in this case), a normal chest X-ray would suggest latent tuberculosis infection rather than active disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are only indicated if there are symptoms suggestive of active tuberculosis (such as persistent cough, night sweats, weight loss) or if the chest X-ray shows abnormalities. In an asymptomatic patient, sputum cultures are not routinely performed as the first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon gamma release assay\u003C/strong\u003E could provide additional information over tuberculin skin testing, particularly in individuals who may have had prior BCG vaccination (evident from the scar on her upper arm) or non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection, both of which can cause false positive tuberculin skin tests. However, chest X-ray remains the priority to exclude active disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifampicin, isoniazid, pyrazinamide, ethambutol\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is the standard treatment for active tuberculosis but should only be initiated after confirming active disease through appropriate investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoniazid\u003C/strong\u003E monotherapy is one recommended regimen for latent tuberculosis infection, but this diagnosis can only be made after excluding active disease with chest X-ray and clinical assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A positive tuberculin skin test requires chest X-ray to screen for active tuberculosis before considering treatment for latent infection.","An induration of \u226510mm is considered positive in people from high TB-prevalence countries.","BCG vaccination can cause false positive tuberculin skin tests, but chest X-ray remains the priority to exclude active disease."],"references":["Coulter C. Tuberculosis testing. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:489-92. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/july/tuberculosis-testing","Communicable Diseases Network Australia. Tuberculosis \u2013 CDNA National Guidelines for Public Health Units. Canberra: Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care; 2022. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/tuberculosis-cdna-national-guidelines-for-public-health-units"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89568"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"168"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89568"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T13:44:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T13:44:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"168"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107104"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i